\citet{Michalakakis_2021}.
---MKH
****


The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}
  b_{ch,i} = \Delta{G_{f,i}} + \sum_{i}{n_{j}b_{ch,j}} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$,
$n_j$ is the number of moles of an element (in units of $\mathrm{mol_i}$),
and Gibbs energy of formation ($\Delta{G_f}$) is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$.
$\Delta{G_{f}}$ values are taken from \citet[pp.~9.4--9.94]{Dean_1979},
\citet[Table~2]{Gibbs_formation},
and \citet[Appendix~II~B]{Tro_2006}.

The chemical exergy of a mixture ($b_{ch,m}$) is

\begin{equation}\label{eq:}
  b_{ch,m} = \sum_{i}{N_m b_{ch,i}} \, .
\end{equation}

%..............................
\paragraph{Concentration exergy ($b_c$)}
\label{sssec:concentration_exergy}
%..............................

The concentration exergy of a mixture ($b_{c,m}$) is the the minimum work required
to separate the mixture into pure compounds.
The definition of concentration exergy is derived from the entropy of mixing.
The entropy of a mixture ($\Delta{S_m}$) is the increase in entropy
that occurs when different substances are mixed reversibly and isothermally
and is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:specific_entropy_of_mixture_definition}
  \Delta{S_m} = -RN_m(y_{1}\ln{y_{1}} + y_{2}\ln{y_{2}} + y_{3}\ln{y_{3}} + \ldots)
          = -RN_m\sum_{i} y_{i}\ln{y_{i}} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\Delta{S_m}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m \cdot K}$,
and $R$ is the universal gas constant (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol \cdot K}$), and
$y_i$ are in $\mathrm{mol_i/mol_m}$.

The reference points for concentrations ($y_i$) are
species as pure substances,
so $y_{i,0} \equiv 1$.

The concentration exergy of a compound (as defined above)
is the reversible work needed to concentrate it to the pure state.
\citet{Valero_2015}
****
Include page number.
---MKH
****
define concentration exergy of a compound ($b_{c,i}$) as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy}
  b_{c,i} = RT_0[\ln(y_i) - \ln(y_{i,0})] \, .
\end{equation}
%

Simplifying Equation (\ref{eq:concentration_exergy})
with $y_{i,0} = 1$ gives

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy_definition}
  b_{c,i} = R T_0 \ln(y_i) \, .
\end{equation}
%
The concentration exergy of a compound in a mixture
is always negative
because the pure substance
in the reference environment
becomes less concentrated
at any statepoint.

The minimum work required to separate a mixture reversibly
at constant temperature and pressure is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:work}
    W_{min} = -T_0\Delta{S_m}
            = R T_0 N_m \sum_{i}(y_i\ln{y_i}) \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $W_{min}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m}$.
The minimum work is negative
because the environment puts work
into the mixture.

%..............................
\paragraph{Elements ($j$)}
\label{sssec:elements}
%..............................

We take chemical exergies of elements ($b_{ch,j}$)
from the crepuscular earth model
of \citet[Table~9.1]{Valero_2015}.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy of energy}
\label{sec:exergy_of_energy}
%------------------------------

The example MCC has both material and energy inputs to processes.
We calculate the exergy of energy as
shown in Equation~(\ref{eq:general_material_exergy_definition})
for all energy sources with mass (e.g., coal, oil, and natural gas).
The exergy of energy inputs are determined by
Equation~(\ref{eq:chemical_exergy_definition})
when the Gibbs energy of formation
($\Delta{G_{f}}$)
is available.
Otherwise (such as for coal and fuel oil),
we calculate material exergy by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_fuels}
  \varepsilon_i = [LHV_i + w h_{fg}]\phi_i + (9417~\mathrm{kJ/kg}) \, s
\end{equation}
%
where $\varepsilon_i$ is the exergy of energy (in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$),
$LHV_i$ is the lower heating value of the fuel (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kg}$),
$w$ is the fuel's mass fraction of moisture (in units of $\mathrm{kg/kg}$),
$h_{fg}$ is the enthalpy of evaporation of \ce{H2O} (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kg}$),
$\phi_i$ is the ratio of exergy to energy (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kJ}$),
the constant 9417~kJ/kg is the difference
in rhombic sulfur's chemical exergy and it's lower heating value,
and $s$ is the mass fraction of sulfur in the fuel (in units of $\mathrm{kg/kg}$).
(See \citet[Eq.~C.5a]{Kotas_1995}.)
We obtain $\phi$ values from \citet[Appendix~C]{Kotas_1995}.
(See Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix_phi}
for solid and liquid fuel exergy equations.)

All other energy sources in the example MCC are electricity.
The exergy of energy at any statepoint
is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X_i = \phi_i E_i \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $X_i$ is the exergy of energy of a species (in units of kJ),
$\phi_i$ is the exergy to energy ratio (unitless),
and $E_i$ is the energy of a species (in units of kJ).
Note $\phi_{electricity} \equiv 1$, by definition.

%------------------------------
\subsubsection{PSUT framework and $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices}
\label{sec:psut_framework}
%------------------------------

The native data format for the ECCs and XCCs
of the CL-PFU database~\citep{Brockway:2024ab} is
the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices%
\footnote{
  Note that matrices are represented by capital letters in bold, non-italic font.
  Vectors are represented by lower-case or script letters in bold, non-italic font.
}
%
of the
Physical Supply-Use Table (PSUT) framework~\citep{Heun:2018,Aramendia:2022tv}.
Although the PSUT framework has been applied
to analysis of energy conversion chains
(both ECCs and XCCs)~\citep{Heun:2019aa,Aramendia:2024ac},
this paper represents its first application to
material conversion chains (MCCs and BCCs) and
to unified exergy analysis of material and energy conversion chains (BXCCs).

One benefit of the PSUT framework
is that it provides a natural structure for data in
material conversion chains (MCCs in mass units),
energy conversion chains (ECCs in energy units), and
exergy conversion chains
(BCCs for material,
XCCs for energy, and
BXCCs for unified,
all in exergy units).
We apply that structure to the conversion chains
developed in Section~\ref{sec:results} below.
The four matrices of the PSUT framework
are
the resource matrix ($\mat{R}$), which contains exogeneous inputs to a conversion chain;
the use matrix ($\mat{U}$), which includes the consumption of materials and energy;
the make matrix ($\mat{V}$), which describes the production of materials and energy
by processes in conversion chains; and
the final demand matrix ($\mat{Y}$), which contains consumption
of materials and energy by economic sectors.
See Figure~\ref{fig:psut_framework_mats}.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.6\linewidth]{images/PSUTmats.pdf}
\caption{Matrices of the PSUT framework. After \citet[Figure~1]{Aramendia:2022tv}.}
\label{fig:psut_framework_mats}
\end{figure}

In the PSUT framework,
processing stages are generically called ``industries,'' and
flows of mass, energy, or exergy between processing stages
are generically called ``products.''
In a flow diagram,
industries are represented visually by boxes.
Products are represented visually by arrows
that indicate the direction of product flow
from one industry to another.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Material and energy conversion chains}
\label{sec:conversion_chains}
%------------------------------

To illustrate application of the exergy of materials
to societal exergy analysis,
we develop several material and energy conversion chains
using the the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the PSUT framework.
First, we develop a direct energy input and material flow model (DEIMFM).
The DEIMFM includes all material flows and \emph{direct} energy inputs.%
\footnote{
  Direct energy inputs are consumed directly by a machine,
  such as electricity consumed by crushers.
  Indirect energy inputs include upstream resources to create
  the direct energy inputs, such as coal used to make electricity.
}

Next, we develop two matrix representations of the mass flows of the DEIMFM.
(a) A mass-only version (MCC) that quantifies material flows in mass units
    from extraction through a blast furnace
    to the Iron and steel industry
    (Section~\ref{sec:material_data}).
(b) An exergy version (BCC) that quantifies material flows in exergy units.
Each statepoint in the MCC is converted to exergy
to form the BCC in accordance with
the methods discussed in Section~\ref{sec:exergy_of_materials}.

Then, we develop two versions of an independent
energy conversion chain to supply the DEIMFM's energy requirements:
(c) an independent energy conversion chain (ECC) obtained from the CL-PFU database
    where all flows are in energy terms
    as described in Sections~\ref{sec:energy_data} and~\ref{sec:ecc_for_mcc}
    and
(d) an independent exergy version of the energy conversion chain (XCC),
    also extracted from the CL-PFU database.
To obtain the ECC and XCC,
we perform an ``upstream swim'' from a new final demand ($\mat{Y}$) matrix
populated with the energy requirements of the BCC,
as discussed in~\citet[Section~2.2.5]{Heun:2018}.

Finally, we develop
(e) a matrix representation of a unified conversion chain (BXCC) that
    brings the exergy of materials and energy together,
    as described in Section~\ref{sec:creating_bxcc} below.
The benefit of unifying the independent material and energy conversion chains
is that all upstream activities for the MCC and ECC are accounted in the BXCC.

