%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Inter-industry balances}
\label{sec:inter-industry_balances}
%------------------------------

When constructing the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the PSUT framework,
we perform an important consistency check
via balances of inter-industry product flows.
The matrix equation for inter-industry product balances is

\begin{equation} \label{eq:inter_industry_balances}
  (\mat{iR})^\mathrm{T} + (\mat{iV})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{Ui} - \mat{y} \overset{?}{=} \mat{0} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where
$\mat{i}$ is a unity row or column vector of appropriate length,
$\mat{iR}$ gives column sums of the resource matrix (a row vector),
$^\mathrm{T}$ is the transpose operator,
$\mat{iV}$ gives column sums of the make matrix (a row vector),
$\mat{Ui}$ gives row sums of the use matrix (a column vector), and
$\mat{y} \equiv \mat{Yi}$ is the row sums of the final demand matrix (a column vector).
The result is a column vector with products in rows.

Regardless of the type of conversion chain
(MCC, BCC, ECC, XCC, BXCC),
Equation~(\ref{eq:inter_industry_balances}) tests whether
all products extracted from resources ($\mat{R}$) or
produced by industries ($\mat{V}$)
become inputs to industries ($\mat{U}$) or
final demand sectors ($\mat{Y}$).
When Equation~(\ref{eq:inter_industry_balances}) is true
(i.e., when the calculation on the left side produces the $\mat{0}$ vector),
the conversion chain is internally consistent.

All matrix representations of conversion chains
developed for this paper
pass the inter-industry consistency check.


