%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Arranging material and energy conversion chain data
in the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the PSUT framework
provides many benefits to analysts.
This section discusses further applications
beyond the contributions shown in Section~\ref{sec:results} above.
In particular, without the PSUT framework,
analyses of all transformation processes (industries) involve repetitive
calculations, once for each process.
With the PSUT framework,
the repetitive calculations can be expressed as a single matrix equation
that performs the analyses for all industries
in a conversion chain.
The interpretation of the results varies,
depending on the type of conversion chain under consideration.
We demonstrate below
the benefits of the PSUT framework
by discussing
across-industry balances (Section~\ref{sec:across_industry_balances}) and
industry efficiencies (Section~\ref{sec:efficiency}).


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Across-industry balances}
\label{sec:across_industry_balances}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In contrast to the inter-industry balances
of Equation~(\ref{eq:inter_industry_balances}),
across-industry balances do not and should not always
calculate to the $\mat{0}$ vector.
Instead, across-industry balances calculate important quantities
depending on the information contained in the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices,
possibly mass flows, energy flows, or exergy flows.
Across-industry balances for every industry
in a conversion chain are given by the matrix equation

\begin{equation} \label{eq:across_industry_balances}
  (\mat{iU})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{Vi} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where
$\mat{iU}$ gives column sums of the use matrix,
$^\mathrm{T}$ indicates the transpose, and
$\mat{Vi}$ gives row sums of the make matrix.
The result of Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances})
is a column vector with industries in rows.

In the following subsections,
we discuss calculations using across-industry balances for
mass, heat loss, and irreversibility.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Across-industry mass balances: mass losses}
\label{sec:across_industry_mass}
%------------------------------

For an MCC, the across-industry balance of
Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances}) becomes

\begin{equation} \label{eq:across_industry_mass}
  \mat{m}_{loss} = (\mat{iU}_{MCC})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{V}_{\!MCC}\mat{i} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\mat{m}_{loss}$ is a vector of mass losses
in which rownames are processing stages and
the subscript ``MCC'' indicates mass versions of the
$\mat{U}$ and $\mat{V}$ matrices.

For an MCC with all waste flows included
(as in the example in this paper),
the across-industry balance of
Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_mass})
becomes

\begin{equation} \label{eq:across_industry_mass_with_0}
   \mat{m}_{loss} = (\mat{iU}_{MCC})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{V}_{\!MCC}\mat{i} = \mat{0} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where the $\mat{0}$ vector on the right side
of Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_mass_with_0})
indicates that mass is conserved.
The example MCC of Section~\ref{sec:results}
is mass-balanced across industries,
as shown in Table~\ref{tab:across_industry_M_loss}.

<<MassLossTable, echo=FALSE, results=tex>>=
print_efficiencies_table(efficiencies_table_name = "M_across_industry_balance_M_loss",
                         latex_label = "tab:across_industry_M_loss",
                         digits = 3,
                         caption = paste("Mass losses ($m_{loss}$) in the",
                                         "example material conversion chain."),
                         size = "footnotesize")
@


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Across-industry energy balances: heat losses}
\label{sec:across_industry_heat_losses}
%------------------------------

For an ECC with no heat losses included
(as in the example of Section~\ref{sec:results}),
the across-industry balance
of Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances})
calculates heat loss from each industry:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:across_industry_heat}
  \mat{Q}_{loss} = (\mat{iU}_{ECC})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{V}_{\!ECC}\mat{i} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where the subscript ``$ECC$'' indicates energy versions of the
$\mat{U}$ and $\mat{V}$ matrices obtained by

\begin{equation}
  \mat{U}_{ECC} = (\mat{U}_{MCC} \circ \mat{U}_h) + \mat{U}_{elect}
\end{equation}
%
and

\begin{equation}
  \mat{V}_{\!ECC} = (\mat{V}_{\!MCC} \circ \mat{V}_h) + \mat{V}_{elect} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
with
$\circ$ indicating the Hadamard (element-wise) product,
subscript ``$h$'' indicating $\mat{U}$ and $\mat{V}$ matrices
containing enthalpy values, and
subscript ``$elect$'' indicating indicating $\mat{U}$ and $\mat{V}$ matrices
containing only (massless) electricity inputs.
See the supplementary information for the
$\mat{U}_{MCC}$, $\mat{V}_{\!MCC}$,
$\mat{U}_h$, $\mat{V}_h$,
$\mat{U}_{elect}$, $\mat{V}_{\!elect}$,
$\mat{U}_{ECC}$, and $\mat{V}_{ECC}$ matrices
for the example of Section~\ref{sec:results}.
Table~\ref{tab:across_industry_Q_loss} shows
the heat loss vector ($\mat{Q}_{loss}$)
for the example in Section~\ref{sec:results}.

<<HeatLossTable, echo=FALSE, results=tex>>=
print_efficiencies_table(efficiencies_table_name = "BX_across_industry_balance_Q_loss",
                         latex_label = "tab:across_industry_Q_loss",
                         digits = 0,
                         caption = paste("Process heat losses ($Q_{loss}$) in the",
                                         "example material conversion chain."),
                         size = "footnotesize")
@

For industries that simply transport mass
(e.g., hauling),
$Q_{loss}$ is equal to the energy input.

For an ECC that includes heat losses,
the across-industry balance
of Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances})
should calculate the $\mat{0}$ vector.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Across-industry exergy balances: exergy losses and irreversibility}
\label{sec:irreversibility}
%------------------------------

For an exergy conversion chain
(BCC, XCC, or BXCC)
that includes waste heat and mass flows,
the across-industry balance calculates the
thermodynamic irreversibility ($\mathcal{I}$) of
(or exergy destruction by) an industry.
For exergy conversion chains that include waste mass flows
and exclude heat loss terms
(as in the example unified material and energy conversion chain
of this paper),
the across-exergy balance of Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances})
calculates the sum of irreversibility and
exergy loss due to heat dissipation ($\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$).
Equation~(\ref{eq:across_industry_balances}) becomes


\begin{equation} \label{eq:irreversibility_balances}
  \boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}_{BXCC} =
        (\mat{iU}_{BXCC})^\mathrm{T} - \mat{V}_{BXCC}\mat{i} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$ is a column vector of
the sum of irreversibility (or exergy destruction)
and exergy loss due to heat dissipation
with industries in rows.
Table~\ref{tab:across_industry_irreversibilities} shows
irreversibilities for the example conversion chains
of Section~\ref{sec:results}.
Exergy is destroyed across all industries,
unless the process is trivial
(e.g., coke oven gas distribution).

<<IrreversibilitiesTable, echo=FALSE, results=tex>>=
print_efficiencies_table(efficiencies_table_name = "I_BXCC",
                         latex_label = "tab:across_industry_irreversibilities",
                         digits = 0,
                         caption = paste("Irreversibilities",
                                         "($\\boldsymbol{\\mathcal{I}}_{BXCC}$) in the",
                                         "example unified material and",
                                         "energy conversion chain."),
                         size = "footnotesize")
@

The irreversibilities and loss of exergy at a process
is determined by the exergy inputs and outputs
to the process,

\begin{equation}\label{eq:irreversibility}
  \boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}} = \sum_{in}{B_m + I_m} - \sum_{out}{B_m + I_m} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
is the irreversibility (or exergy destruction) of the process,
$B_{in,m}$ is the exergy of a mixture going into a process,
and $B_{out,m}$ is the exergy of a mixture leaving a process
(all in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$).
% ****
% Perhaps the narrative here should be expanded to cover the exergy
% of massless inputs and outputs, namely heat and electricity.
% ---MKH
% ****
$I$ should never be a negative value because exergy can not be generated,
only destroyed.

The exergy lost ($B_{lost}$) from a process is given by
\begin{equation}\label{exergy_lost}
  B_{lost} = \sum_{out}{B_{k,m,waste}}
\end{equation}
%
where $B_{k,m,waste}$ is the exergy of a waste stream
from a process (in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$).
The embodied exergy is the exergy loss
in a supply chain,
give by
\begin{equation}\label{embodied_exergy}
  B_{em} = \sum{B_{lost}}
\end{equation}
%
where $B_{em}$ is the embodied exergy
(in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$).


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Efficiencies}
\label{sec:efficiency}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

We illustrate the application of material exergy to
societal exergy analysis within the PSUT framework
by calculating process efficiencies
throughout the unified conversion chain (BXCC).
There are many ways to calculate the efficiencies of industries
in a material or energy conversion chain.
We demonstrate two methods here:
the rational efficiency and the resource efficiency.

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{images/example_process_diagram.pdf}
  \caption{An example process for efficiency methods.}
  \label{fig:example_process_diagram}
\end{figure}


Irreversibility arises from thermodynamic inefficiencies.
Exergy loss arises from unused outputs, i.e.,
wastes, including mass and heat.

To illustrate calculations for the rational and resource efficiencies,
we employ Figure~\ref{fig:example_process_diagram} which shows
an example process (industry) within a conversion chain.
Inputs $R$ and $E$ represent material resources and energy inputs, respectively.
Output $P$ represents beneficial products,
output $W_M$ represents material waste products.
and output $W_Q$ represents heat waste.
Note that additional resource, energy input, product, or waste streams
can be present in real processes.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Rational efficiencies}
\label{sec:rational_efficiency}
%------------------------------

The rational efficiency method accounts for all process outputs
in the numerator and all process inputs in the denominator.
With reference to Figure~\ref{fig:example_process_diagram},
\citet[Equation~(2.45)]{Dincer_2007}
define the rational efficiency efficiency as

\begin{equation} \label{eq:rational_efficiency_process}
  \eta_{rational} = \frac{B_P + B_{W,M}}{X_{elect} + B_R} \, .
\end{equation}
%
where $X_{elect}$ is the exergy of energy input E.
Equation~(\ref{eq:rational_efficiency_process}) must be applied separately
to each process in a conversion chain.

In the PSUT framework,
Equation~(\ref{eq:rational_efficiency_process})
can be re-cast as a matrix equation
that applies to all processes in a conversion chain.

\begin{equation} \label{eq:rational_efficiency_psut}
  \boldsymbol{\upeta}_{rational} = (\widehat{\mat{iU}}_{BXCC})\!^{-1} (\mat{V}_{\!BXCC}\mat{i}) \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where
$\boldsymbol{\upeta}_{rational}$ is a column vector of rational efficiencies
for transformation processs with industries in rows,
the~~$\widehat{~}$~~symbol indicates diagonalization
of the $\mat{iU}$ vector into a square matrix, and
$^{-1}$ indicates matrix inversion.
Table~\ref{tab:process_efficiencies} shows rational efficiencies
for the example BXCC in Section~\ref{sec:results}.

