%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Resource efficiencies}
\label{sec:resource_efficiency}
%------------------------------

The resource approach quantifies
how efficiently a process converts resources
(all inputs) into the desired product of the process.
The resource efficiency removes wastes and
accounts only for beneficial exergy outputs in the numerator
of the efficiency calculation.
Similar to the rational efficiency,
the resource efficiency includes all exergy inputs in the denominator
of the efficiency calculation.
With reference to Figure~\ref{fig:example_process_diagram},
\citet[Equation~(2.44)]{Dincer_2007}
define the resource efficiency efficiency as
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:resource_efficiency_process}
  \eta_{resource} = \frac{B_P}{X_{elect}+ B_R} \, .
\end{equation}
%
Similar to Equation~(\ref{eq:rational_efficiency_process}),
Equation~(\ref{eq:resource_efficiency_process}) must be applied separately
to each process in a conversion chain.

In the PSUT framework,
Equation~(\ref{eq:resource_efficiency_process}) can be re-cast as a matrix equation
that applies to all process in a conversion chain.

\begin{equation} \label{eq:resource_efficiency_psut}
  \boldsymbol{\upeta}_{resource} = (\widehat{\mat{iU}}_{BXCC})\!^{-1} (\mat{V}_{\!BXCC}\mat{i}_P)
\end{equation}
%
Equation~(\ref{eq:resource_efficiency_psut}) is identical to
Equation~(\ref{eq:rational_efficiency_psut}) except that
the make matrix ($\mat{V}_{\!BXCC}$) is post-multiplied by $\mat{i}_P$
instead of by $\mat{i}$.
$\mat{i}_P$ is a product selection vector containing ``1''
for beneficial outputs and ``0'' for wastes.
Table~\ref{tab:process_efficiencies} shows resource efficiencies
for the example BXCC of Section~\ref{sec:results}.

